### Tool Class — `ApiTools.cs`

```csharp
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;
using System.ComponentModel;
using System.Text.Json;

[McpServerToolType]
public class ApiTools(HttpClient httpClient, ILogger<ApiTools> logger)
{
    [McpServerTool, Description("Fetch a resource by its unique identifier.")]
    public async Task<string> GetResource(
        [Description("The unique resource ID")] string id,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        logger.LogInformation("Fetching resource {Id}", id);
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync($"/api/resources/{id}", cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool, Description("Create a new resource with the given name and category.")]
    public async Task<string> CreateResource(
        [Description("Name for the new resource")] string name,
        [Description("Category to assign")] string category,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        var payload = JsonSerializer.Serialize(new { name, category });
        var content = new StringContent(payload, System.Text.Encoding.UTF8, "application/json");

        var response = await httpClient.PostAsync("/api/resources", content, cancellationToken);
        response.EnsureSuccessStatusCode();
        return await response.Content.ReadAsStringAsync(cancellationToken);
    }

    [McpServerTool(ReadOnly = true), Description("Search resources by keyword.")]
    public async Task<string> SearchResources(
        [Description("Search keyword")] string query,
        CancellationToken cancellationToken = default)
    {
        return await httpClient.GetStringAsync(
            $"/api/resources?q={Uri.EscapeDataString(query)}", cancellationToken);
    }
}
```

### `Program.cs` — stdio transport

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.DependencyInjection;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Hosting;
using Microsoft.Extensions.Logging;
using ModelContextProtocol.Server;

var builder = Host.CreateApplicationBuilder(args);

// CRITICAL: log to stderr only — stdout is the JSON-RPC protocol channel
builder.Logging.AddConsole(options =>
    options.LogToStandardErrorThreshold = LogLevel.Trace);

builder.Services.AddHttpClient<ApiTools>(client =>
{
    client.BaseAddress = new Uri("https://api.example.com");
});

builder.Services.AddMcpServer()
    .WithStdioServerTransport()
    .WithToolsFromAssembly();

await builder.Build().RunAsync();
```

### How DI works for MCP tools

The SDK supports **two injection styles**:

| Style | Class type | How services arrive |
|-------|-----------|-------------------|
| **Constructor injection** | Non-static class | Services via constructor params (shown above) |
| **Method injection** | Static class | Services as method params alongside tool args |

**Key rule:** The SDK automatically distinguishes tool parameters from injected services. Types registered in DI (`HttpClient`, `ILogger<T>`, `IMcpServer`, `CancellationToken`, `IProgress<T>`) are **resolved from DI and hidden from the tool schema**. Only parameters with `[Description]` are exposed to the LLM.

For the constructor injection pattern above, `HttpClient` and `ILogger<ApiTools>` are injected when the class is instantiated — the LLM only sees `id`, `name`, `category`, and `query` as callable parameters.

Use **constructor injection** (non-static class) when tools share services or state. Use **method injection** (static class) for simple, stateless tools.
